"Buhl-Mortensen L., Myhr A., Welin S.","Carbon sequestration, the precautionary approach and the responsibility of scientists",2005,"Water Science and Technology","52","6",,"205","212",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-28244442447&partnerID=40&md5=f65d7f4006642dd39ce053e9d3723fe9","Institute of Marine Research, P.B. 1870 Nordnes, N-5817 Bergen, Norway; Norwegian Institute of Gene Ecology, The Science Park, N-9294 Tromsø, Norway; Department of Technology and Social Change, Linköping University, SE-58183 Linköping, Sweden","Buhl-Mortensen, L., Institute of Marine Research, P.B. 1870 Nordnes, N-5817 Bergen, Norway; Myhr, A., Norwegian Institute of Gene Ecology, The Science Park, N-9294 Tromsø, Norway; Welin, S., Department of Technology and Social Change, Linköping University, SE-58183 Linköping, Sweden","This paper reviews problems connected to the use of the deep-sea and sub-sea geological formations for carbon sequestration. We will focus on the risks and dangers involved in using this kind of large-scale engineering approach, which is not yet fully tested, to combat global warming. We will not provide a complete discussion on the technologies involved, but concentrate on a few principal questions, such as the responsibility of environmental scientists involved in this research. We will also discuss carbon sequestration in relation to the precautionary approach. We argue that there may be a place for large-scale engineering attempts, but this should be the last rather than the first option. © IWA Publishing 2005.","Carbon sequestration; Precautionary approach; Responsibility of scientists","Air pollution control; Aquifers; Ecosystems; Environmental impact; Gas emissions; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Waste disposal; Carbon sequestration; Large-scale engineering; Precautionary approach; Carbon dioxide; carbon sequestration; precautionary principle; carbon sequestration; deep sea; engineering; environmental protection; geology; greenhouse eff